# gate-paths — the ONE canonical list of "the gate layer" for this repository.
#
# This file is the single source of truth for which paths, when changed in a pull
# request, require an independent gate-review before they may merge to main (see
# CONTRIBUTING.md "Governance"). `gate-review-check.py` reads THIS file; the policy
# prose points here rather than re-listing the paths, so the machine's notion of
# "the gate layer" cannot drift from the documented one. (That drift — a gate's
# self-description diverging from what it actually does — is exactly the failure
# class this whole governance layer exists to catch. We refuse to repeat it in our
# own tooling: there is one list, and everything derives from it.)
#
# Why these paths are "the gates that guard the suite": each one can pass CI green
# while silently weakening or mis-describing a check. CI green is necessary but not
# sufficient for them; they additionally require human/independent judgement.
#
# Matching semantics (kept deliberately small and testable):
#   - a line ending in "/"      -> directory subtree: matches any changed path that
#                                   starts with that prefix (e.g. "tests/").
#   - a line containing "*"      -> fnmatch against the full path AND the basename
#                                   (e.g. "lint-*.py" matches "lint-skill-count.py").
#   - any other line             -> exact full-path match (repo-root-relative).
# Blank lines and lines starting with "#" are ignored.

# --- Build / release orchestration -------------------------------------------------
release-gate.sh
build-skills.sh
pkgtools.py

# --- Validators and the version/changelog gate -------------------------------------
validate_skill.py
check-version.py

# --- Suite lints (current AND any future lint-*.py) --------------------------------
lint-*.py

# --- The shared documentation verifier (the gate consumers + the golden tests run) -
shared/verify.py

# --- The gates that guard the gates ------------------------------------------------
tests/

# --- CI + the governance / enforcement layer itself (self-protecting) --------------
# Changing how merges are gated is itself a gate-layer change: a weakened workflow,
# a narrowed gate-paths list, a softened policy, or a relaxed check must not slip in
# unreviewed. So the enforcement layer guards itself.
.github/
gate-review-check.py
gate-review-prompt.md
CONTRIBUTING.md
